<h2>Wyoming Incentives & Rebates</h2>

<p>Wyoming homeowners benefit from several valuable incentives that significantly reduce the cost of solar and HVAC improvements. The federal solar Investment Tax Credit (ITC) provides a 30% credit for solar panel installations through 2032, stepping down to 26% in 2033 and 22% in 2034. This credit applies to the total system cost, including equipment, installation, and applicable sales taxes, making it one of the most valuable solar incentives available.</p>

<p>Wyoming's property tax exemption for solar energy systems ensures that homeowners don't pay additional property taxes on the increased value from solar installations. This exemption, combined with the lack of state income tax, means Wyoming residents keep more of their solar savings compared to other states. The exemption applies to both the equipment and installation costs, providing ongoing value throughout the system's lifetime.</p>

<p>Rocky Mountain Power offers net metering programs that credit solar customers at retail rates for excess electricity fed back to the grid. The utility's Schedule 136 allows systems up to 25kW to participate, with monthly netting and annual true-ups. Additionally, Rocky Mountain Power provides energy efficiency rebates for qualifying HVAC equipment, including up to \$1,000 for high-efficiency heat pumps and \$200-500 for Energy Star furnaces and air conditioners. These rebates, combined with federal tax credits and local utility programs, can reduce HVAC upgrade costs by 20-40%.</p>

<p>The Database of State Incentives for Renewables & Efficiency (DSIRE) tracks additional local incentives that may be available in specific Wyoming municipalities. Some areas offer expedited permitting for solar installations, reduced permit fees, or additional rebates for energy storage systems. Homeowners should also investigate federal and state tax credits for geothermal systems, which can provide up to 30% federal credits for qualifying installations through 2034.</p>

